Dietary of an obese child: breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems with being overweight, with overweight being 9 percent of schoolchildren and obese being 5 percent of children.
Obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, according to a recent study.
Once again, it shows how important it is for the healthy development of the environment in which a person grows and the patterns that surround him.
For example, on tables in obese children, bruises appear up to half more often than in families of children with normal weight.
Fried fries had for dinner the day before the research associated with the outreach event called Obesity is no coincidence more than 19 percent of obese.
In obese families, too, it is not customary to do sports, which, of course, affects most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children responded that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last year’s school year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was already the second year of the Obesity Not a coincidence event, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 students from the 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
Proper eating and enough exercise in the family is one of the determining factors that causes the dramatically increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
“Only half of those surveyed, for example, said they ate breakfast-breakfast-lunch-dinner-dinner five times a day, which is one of the basic assumptions of proper nutrition,” the study said.
Without breakfast and evening steak
Experts point out that for healthy development, both relative details are essential, including, for example, the regular time of family breakfasts.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of schoolchildren eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
And the worst part was finding out that in a tenth of households, they don’t eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly exercise, the result for their parents was less than half - 15 percent.
Build your own meal plan
Another part of the survey allowed the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own meal plan according to their own taste and opinion.
"The nutritional preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of floury, meaty and sweet dishes.
"The alarming popularity of sweet lemonade is particularly high," the study's final report said.
At lunchtime, pasta was the main dish just above the poultry.
But the children practically did not want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and lunch vegetables is low.
Propensity for health
The survey also showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"The control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the obesity education lecture was not a coincidence, in a number of cases, there was a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy eating," the project's results say.
For example, in the case of sweet lemonades, more children would start to prefer ordinary water.
Children also checked poultry and fish as the main meal of the day much more often in the questionnaire, and would restrict sweet foods and dumplings.
