Need for Speed: The Run takes place across the Americas.
Review(s)
Originally, a carefree ride is transformed into a routine morning walk due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
Although the ambition has largely been fulfilled, it is not valid if no one clearly wanted to do anything extra.
A new episode titled The Run aroused high expectations before it was released.
He promised that the year-old racing series Need for Speed would once again move a bit in a new direction and from playable demonstrations it appeared as a game that in the genre of action racing would not have to be just in numbers.
We were also curious how the embedded passages, in which the main hero gets out of the car and runs on his own.
As usual with the NFS series, however, many things are a little different from what we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole thing pulls down a few unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing in the series for more than a few years.
So it’s not really a mistake, but rather an expression of some incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are introduced to the story whose main hero Jack has certain problems of a personal nature and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You will be driving on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to be the first to arrive in New York.
The idea carries with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race runs on a different track and the given stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t even feel like the game is always the same.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing world-famous.
But driving through the desert, the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains seems visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are occasionally plastered with some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught up in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you need to be careful not to get overwhelmed by an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are quite well-developed.
There are only a few types, but that’s enough.
For a while you try to overcome the required number of opponents (essentially a classic race), then again you reach the time (classical match with the bars) and then there is a duel with a single opponent waiting for you.
From time to time, the police will also be involved, which further upsets your efforts.
The novelty is the passages outside the car.
Rather, it’s just such an interactive animation, where Jack usually runs in front of someone and you have to help him with it by pressing the right buttons at the right times.
It's nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, however, these passages are much less in the game than you would expect (in particular, maybe only three).
As a result, however, it is for the benefit of the thing, because this element does not have a chance to become annoying and in the context of the above, it belongs to the elements that diversify the game.
The riding model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that nowadays it is definitely no longer who knows, but it cannot be said to be a negative.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the more action-packed racing model here still fits quite well, even though we could find a better one in the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
Problems begin to appear after a while.
Unlike the car model, it is no longer a collision model.
From a game of this type, we do not expect it to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how your car will behave before any impact on any object, then probably not everything is completely fine.
Typically, when you’re just overtaking or switching cars in normal traffic, sometimes you just lick each other slightly, but sometimes in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even a direct attack.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn’t matter, but it will detune you reliably.
Restarts are solved in such a way that if you crash or go far off track, the game will throw you back to the last catch point on the track.
There are only five restarts available in each race.
When you have exhausted them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
So it’s more like a help in case something doesn’t work out than you could rely on them explicitly.
But sometimes even restarts do not help, they only solve the need to learn a certain section of the race memory.
The big problem with the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some bends, for example, need to pass in a specific way, otherwise you simply won’t fit in.
At other times, you will meet "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially aggravating in situations where you see the opponent passing easily in front of you between two opposing cars, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to bypass or brake them.
It does not matter when you reach them, because it is "calculated" so that the given situation always occurs right in front of your nose.
Opponents have another advantage.
Throughout the game, you will encounter several places where, again, regardless of the time, you will always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
It hits most at the end of the game on a long bridge, where you drive in the opposite direction.
The opponent has to get there in front of you apparently at any cost.
When he drives in front of you, it worsens your visibility of the counter-going cars, so at the beginning you spread out there a few times.
You can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-filled, but the execution is so obvious that it reliably disgusts you quickly.
And it's a pity, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and places are so action-packed that sometimes you literally don't tend to watch where everything flies.
And it doesn’t really matter whether it’s a concept with fifty unique tracks, a race schedule so that boredom doesn’t have a chance, or anything else.
An unconventional idea is to exchange cars during races.
You have to be careful of gas stations on the roads, because that’s where you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you’ll be satisfied with what you have right now.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports bikes are suitable for urban areas, strong American storms on straight highways and exotic supersports for technical riding, for example on rolling mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand with both the challenge modes, which are the races in the individual locations you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points in your profile, which is common for challenges and stories.
To gain a higher level of the driver, various items are unlocked: starting with the car and ending with the background for the profile.
At the same time, it is also linked to the online Autolog feature, which, among other things, compares your achieved results with other players and provides additional community features.
One of the other hard to understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you will get to the subway tunnel (either), where you take it in the dark along the tracks (either).
On the tachometer, the numbers flash between 150 and 200 km/h (because) and a set of subway stops at the back and uncompromisingly knocks you down.
In the editorial office, we will have a discussion for a few more days about whether no one really thought about it when creating the game, or whether the authors consider us to be such a big asshole.
The technical side of the game is nothing extra, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in a few cases even great.
It is unfortunate that in some of the more exhausting moments, the shooting decreases, and in some cases quite tragically.
But this is especially true for a drill with a larger number of participants, when smooth shooting would no longer be valid for you.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, the soundtrack was created from the category "every dog is different", but it can be assumed that because of listening to music, no one will buy the game.
Need for Speed: The Run is a bit of a mess.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best NFS game in the last few years.
This is how the game is unfinished.
Fun is certainly fine, but be prepared for the fact that mistakes will tear you in the eye with the power of airport spotlights.
