IBM's History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally under the complex name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM did not take over until 1924 - it was originally a brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
IBM was founded on the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous "squirrels," i.e. clocks recording the employee's arrival and departure.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the company's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of a rival company, to help him manage the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founders of IBM - Watson's ideas are still built on an invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name implies, began manufacturing and selling all kinds of business machines – from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years of Watson’s leadership, revenue doubled to $9 million, and the company’s extensive expansion into all continents began.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after almost forty years in the chief's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, humans and computers from IBM helped NASA fly into space – to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous man’s flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360.
The classic "slice" that set the computer standard at the time, called IBM 5150, came to the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to Chinese company Lenovo, bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers, and began to devote itself fully to consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make smart use of technology in unplanned areas and to improve the situation, for example in transport or city administration.
For the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smarter Commerce” platform, which helps merchants manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the country.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM, the Czech Republic also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central Office for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition.
