How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc in the vast majority, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled on holiday to the DDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea by the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when there was also the possibility of traveling to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the travels of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the era of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually, even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand a queue overnight with a sleeping bag or to have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
However, it was not won either.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a prerequisite for travel to the West, was not given to “politically unreliable people” who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it was not possible to obtain funds (western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange promise.
By far the most often, however, the Czechs spent holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs bought and this custom survives to this day.
Traveling Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our peak, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we do not realize today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the most popular Croatia today until 1989, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Immediately at the end of the 1990s, the visa requirement for neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, mainly to Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czechs slept in parks and tents because our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of the Czechs' travel was at this time driving their own food, cans, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally freely buy the Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living and, with it, our average wages have risen, leading to another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare for charter flights since 1997, making air travel incredibly cheaper than in the past due to the possibility of contracting quantitative discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free access to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the United States, which continued to make our travels easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the Czech Republic was historically the first direct charter flight to exoticism, it was to Thailand.
From this year onwards, Czech tourists fly direct charters to warm distant countries every year, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States revoked the visa for Czech tourists and thus our country was finally ranked among the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than CZK 15 thousand per person on one foreign holiday, including the cost of residence.
