After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy – just go to Facebook.
“We realized that getting them isn’t that hard at all,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently released report by the UK research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, Bartlett says, that scientists had enough to simply use the ads on the site and thus accurately identify the demographic group they were looking for – something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups to be optimistic about them, and then they turned their attention to them and sent them advertisements. But instead of inviting them into a newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they called them to meet their demands.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries – without having to leave the office at all.
“It’s a whole new way of doing research,” Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are generally young men who are describing an increasing rate of immigration.
