The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and political researchers use this site to study everything from health problems to social trends hiding with state updates, wall posts, and the pressed "Like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them will provide three different data on an average daily, which makes this social network literally an "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic papers, in the name of which the word "Facebook" appears on the front page of the 800%, has risen over the
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"In the past, when you wanted to conduct a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to a side where they'd never let you go," Bartlett says.
“Facebook is breaking down all this – you’re just going straight to them.”
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a socio-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken outcomes on Facebook were much more at risk for the problem of alcoholism than students who remained silent about the topic.
Moreno suggests that student peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"The problem can't be solved unless you can diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Children's Health, Behaviour and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children that we would otherwise not have a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The website's information team has compiled statistics on the relationship status and Valentine's Day, election turnout in 2010 and the nation's satisfaction ratio (mainly using the information they had accessed - Internet freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its research information treasure more accessible).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the ability to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site needs to provide their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data offline. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
“I don’t think most users even thought that scientists could look at their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using his students’ public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it as information only between them and their friends."
Then there is also the question of methodology.
Even with offline research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
It is not possible to verify on Facebook how much of the information on the profile and posts on the wall are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn said.
That’s why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, thinks that the pencil and notebook are still the best possible tool that can be used in research.
