Ninety days later, we were able to make a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How big companies are breathing:
Long before leading Apple’s resurrection, Jobs prudently predicted that many industry leaders would slump in their vision and lose their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, well, what's next?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can no longer be more successful.
