The lie has been able to destroy entire careers and enclose the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately refuted by indisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was accused of misusing his campaign finances to try to conceal his unmarried relationship.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that crashed around Bill Clinton when he lied in the second period about his sexual intercourse with Monica Lewinsky.
Everywhere there are stories of cheating at school and at university.
There are times when teachers themselves give their students test answers just to make them look good in their assessments.
Mentors, who should teach the opposite, send a message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How many frauds do we face?
Studies show that in a single day you will find somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Suppose that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times during the first ten minutes of their first encounter.
Determining lies, or “recognizing lies,” is an essential skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or work reasons.
But it's not a social game that's like, say, Sharad, when a person shouts, "I have you." Deception recognition is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the last six decades in the field of psychology, project universities and research in the course of detailed research.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
The liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're sneezing, sneezing, reddening, or messing around.
But don’t assume that it’s hard to spot and uncover a liar.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from the sentence structure, small expressions in the face, the way questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from a vast and evolving industry related to the recognition of lies, and it is clear that the detection of lies is a modern skill that can be easily learned and in today's complex world can help you a lot - especially in the case of leadership, especially if it is one of your occupations.
Good liars are able to read well in others, let them be immersed in vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more “self-centered” lies, while women say more lies “focused on others” – mostly to protect someone’s feelings – that married people lie less often to their partners than single people do.
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called “early observation.”
Thanks to him, he will have later findings with which to compare.
