In an exclusive interview for Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that for them the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This is what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The band is on tour in South America to celebrate its 20th anniversary and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday 20th.
This day will perform from 19:30 at the National Stadium together with the angel group The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an example of an interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the La Nación website.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The journey to Costa Rica is also our dream, which becomes a reality.
In South and Central America we are barely the second time and the experiences so far have been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It's a wonderful country and I believe we will be able to stay here for a few days.
So we're very happy to be able to bring you our music.
I ask, because here they literally adore the group, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your biggest fans?
Thank you for staying with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve shown in the last 21 years have been made in a matter of weeks.
We did some great shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully we got into shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we love the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you know Costa Rica and its waves suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. So we learned about Costa Rica, through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no limits on what we can't do.
We will try to showcase the best show with a variety of tracks. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's that?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs we’ll play each night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven’t played for a long time, we focus on them and we are also surprised, because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have already forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, and that’s why I think it’s more interesting for people.
This tour celebrates 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, I'm sure you are.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we'd be in one big rock band and that we'd stay in it for more than 20 years, that sounds like a dream.
We realize how much we have been given and it impresses us that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are fortunate to be able to look at the places we have always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which the giants themselves are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends, too often it does not happen.
From time to time, a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud of that and we are honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with some of them.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are fortunate that they are all our friends and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to keep together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think, firstly, we are all lucky to be still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We’re all close friends, and that’s why we’ve managed to open up musical pathways that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We believe in each other, we value each other’s music, and I don’t think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word glory was not easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became increasingly easier to find a balance.
We try not to ride too much on a tour because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you will remember that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You must not be taken away by being famous, rock stars. This has never really interested either of us.
What do you think of Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote great songs and at the beginning it was something great.
As a band, we existed for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating, because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we make friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember how happy I was with Andy, how unbelievable he was.
She was an incredible person and we miss her so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to launch the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as the forerunners?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious what Las Robertas will offer live and must be very fun.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bass player?
Lots of people.
Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all night about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge even though it’s no longer in fashion?
I think we've always felt slightly separated from the word grunge.
When it comes to grunge, I imagine the bands that I mentioned like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came into being at the same time. And if music is still valid today, it's something great, because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney don't play today.
At first, your music had a slightly gloomy character, and now it’s more positive.
What is behind this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there are a few tracks on the new album that are lighter-looking, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they can sound like positive.
At both of them, when Ed played it for me, I was crying, and those songs are deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think that you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
