Fujimori hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower limbs, his doctor said.
72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several illnesses, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and doctors are currently under control.
MEP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told TV station Canal N that Fujimori will undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases within three days to find out why he is hurting and why he is losing strength in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga said he believes Fujimori could get pardon for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself does not wish to be pardoned because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times for cancer of the tongue, shed 18 kilograms and added to these problems other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, cysts on the pancreas, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor noted.
Fujimori has served his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murder squad of the army operating illegally in the first years of his rule.
