The official delegation, led by the President of Uruguay, José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and entrepreneurs, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday. It aims to achieve the expansion of trade between the two nations and touch on the political themes of the given region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, on Wednesday. This is the most important meeting of a large-scale visit full of meetings with representatives of politics, commerce and representatives of the Uruguayan community living in Mexico. The program was published by the Uruguayan Presidential Office.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political issues between the two countries," the Uruguayan presidential office said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica will try to persuade Calderón to support Uruguay in a dispute with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on the list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that would continue to remain in the position of tax havens would be excluded from the international community, prompting a rejection of Uruguay's position and consultation with the ambassador to that European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November. The G20 is a group formed by the world’s most powerful developing and developed countries. With the aforementioned Latin American country, an agreement on the exchange of information has been concluded since January of this year to prevent double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has sought to concretize fiscal exchange agreements in order to get out of the "blacklist" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not implemented all the required international standards of cooperation in the field of taxation.
From a trade point of view, Mexico and Uruguay have concluded a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has strengthened the exchange of goods between the two countries.
