Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature.
If tiling were properly taken care of, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 spills after each rainy season in the Valle de México metropolitan area, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, who at the same time added that if the construction, construction and maintenance of asphalt were to be done, it would be necessary to repair the spills.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Exhaustions, which he delivered during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, thus creating a mixture having similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time having greater mechanical resistance, ductility and resistance.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, for example in some cities in the north of the country.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is the grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a high molecular weight called asphalts, and others with a low molecular weight called malts. Together, they give the asphalt a typical character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt lies in the fact that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperatures, the chemical engineering expert noted.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible tiles, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the topmost layers is an asphalt inlay, formed by small stones poured into the asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that forms the insert is filled with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is possible that the forces in the tile are well distributed.
If they were modified asphalt, they would break down even better, according to a chemical engineer.
He added that on the asphalt insert is placed the last layer called the mantle, formed by fine stone, that is, sand also poured into the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with vehicle rims, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the roadway.
Since as part of the paving will be exposed to a large load, the coat must have a sufficient thickness and must be careful of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. Especially water has a big impact on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads in and it is difficult to get out, this causes the softening of all layers of the pavement and thus the formation of debris.
He explained that during the formation of spills, the film of the casing will be destroyed first and only then the asphalt insert will be damaged. But the damage does not occur at one time, but it is a gradual process, which should be stopped at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of debris, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of tile must correspond to the load of vehicles and must be guaranteed that this load will not be exceeded.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of work to be done on asphalt, and research is underway. For example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries, make it easy to repair waste without having to use high temperatures.
