This was the work of a Cali resident who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cana.
The Cali fingerprint expert went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cana".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4th last year, a fingerprint expert from the CTI in Cali entered history as a man who confirmed the identity of the FARC's supreme leader: "Alfonso Cana", by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprint experts working at the CTI department, this week was the turn of Eliasar González, a man from Puerta Tejada who has been working in forensic research for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked at the Chocó Town Hall, where he often had to dig through the forest for more than five days to get to the place where the dead bodies had to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital of Valle and, after taking the relevant courses, began to specialize in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of friction of the skin, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of the operation against Alfonso Cano, Eliasar was told to take his clothes with him for at least three days.
Something big was to be expected.
He left for Cauca on a helicopter from Palmyra on Friday night.
He knew he would have to identify two bodies and that he suspected one of them to be the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to take a card with the fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigative team at the location of the body, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance. It looked completely different than in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a villager in the area, without glasses, much slimmer.
But the prints don't lie.
Together with the galton magnifying glass, ink, and transplanter and light, Eliasar began comparing the dactyl records of the corpse with the records from the card.
The eye did not disappoint her: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, a man from Puerto Tejada was tasked with confirming to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón whether he was really the FARC commander-in-chief.
Searching for tracks
For the dactyloscope from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos gave to Eliazar González at the press conference of the operative service against "Can" is very important.
A lot of people don't know our job.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without the possibility of error, which can play a key role in deciding crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, these people help investigate crimes such as theft or murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When they are caught, many criminals present false documents or have no papers at all.
We'll take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator said that in the event of an injury, he had to remove a piece of the house wall in the house, because this is where the thief leaned to pull out a vault full of jewelry and money.
The walls are difficult because they are not meant to take prints, but in this case we could get a full hand print and identify the perpetrator who was involved in several thefts," he said.
Fingerprints can also confirm or refute suspicions of murder.
Recently, they found a dead man with bottles of alcohol around him.
The investigation revealed that one of the family members could be responsible for the murder, and the print on the bottle actually confirmed it.
Although it cannot be 100% confirmed that he was indeed a murderer, it is obvious that he appeared on the scene of the crime.
The CTI’s fingerprint expert explained that the objects are “cleaned using chemical or physical reactive substances.”
When they appear, a transplantor or tape is used for their collection.
Then the prints are sent to Asif, which is a database of criminals, or to the Registrar.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians whose data is not recorded anywhere," the CTI expert said.
