Europe has invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a rare and fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, for even though it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it experienced the tragedy of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the gulags, but also France in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonels in Greece during the 20th century.
Some people may have believed that in order for democracy to definitively triumph over its enemies, it will be enough to make an election and execute it as directly as possible.
But it is known from Napoleon that it was easy to think.
General suffrage, although it is a necessary condition of democracy, is not sufficient and can become a “instrument of oppression” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization of division and control of power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it has been the same since the beginning of the crisis of politics and democracy.
Admitting the mistake of a Greek yes-no referendum will have the value of a double revelation in this respect: the revelation of the necessity of a great return of political power, but also the revelation of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, its inadequacy.
This ambivalence must be thought of in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic camp have moved today and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer shooting in the right direction.
There is nothing we can achieve if we demand a series of national referendums organised as necessary and disorganized.
White exposed to a European absolutist monarch or a leap with tied legs into the emptiness of nationalist depths: what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not want guillotine knives, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we would not even know where to end the list - because the crisis is in Europe.
Indeed, it is the whole of Europe bowing down to the dictates of markets and credit rating agencies, which suffers from its incompetence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it each of its peoples.
There is an urgent need to restore the governance of the European project of democratic sovereignty.
For only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, get rid of market governments and prepare the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will involve decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise it would lead us to disaster.
After a long struggle against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today is calling for a European economic government.
Come on.
But to think of it without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such citizens, would be a new madness and a new dead end.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
In order for a republic to emerge in France, it was necessary to "be" Republicans.
A revolution of interest could not be enough.
This lesson continues to apply.
We need to build a Europe that is more economically integrated.
This will only be possible by building a more politically democratic Europe and a genuine European democratic sovereignty.
Let us become Europeans in order to build Europe.
