Nord Stream, the new port of entry of Russian gas into Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Eastern Europe directly to Russia and runs along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, is now operational.
It must supply gas equivalent to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to properly celebrate this event.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended Tuesday the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte jointly controlled the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will flow into Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km of pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline, due to be completed by the end of 2012, will provide a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is equal to the total French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge construction is a victory.
Poland and the Baltic States protested strongly against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being flown through the country by any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At once, these two countries are losing a bit of power: the possibility of pressuring Russia with threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that it is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, with its support for this Russian project, gained greater certainty in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, because the project has created rifts between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has barely managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, high-gas-consumption Western states, whose bearings are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us," Fillon said at the opening ceremony of the pipeline, demonstrating at what point large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of the leaders of Gazprom present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The subsea pipe is made of steel with a concrete casing to protect it from the anchorages of marine vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the time of World War II.
“For safety reasons, nearly a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffelovek, which is not interrupted anywhere on its entire length by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project managers rejected it when the Swedes were only unwilling to see the Russian state company permanently settling off their coast.
"In the event of a malfunction, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline leaks into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders, since the welding was designed to cause leakage once every 100,000 years.
The status of the pipeline from the outside is checked by a submarine robot pulled by the ship, while the inside of the pipeline is checked by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pressed with gas.
It will provide accurate information about possible deformations of metal parts in the target at a speed of 3 m/s after a full three days of travel.
The long-distance pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest need for repair.
The circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom remains in the lead, holding a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
The company is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased to the company for a five-year contract, which could be renewed, all of its capacity to transport gas.
“Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, no matter how much gas is actually being transported,” says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% bank loans.
The total cost of work is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, the investment costs amounted to $240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be reimbursed, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline exits the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves with a height of 4.5 meters form the gas outlet gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
