Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed disabled workers?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
Today is the 15th week for the employment of disabled people.
Despite the voluntaristic public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed people with disabilities is even twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% vs. 9% for the entire population.
Is it overwhelming?
"No, underlines Éric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes the Week for the Employment of the Disabled."
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher."
"However, there is still much to be done."
It must be said that there are many obstacles for unemployed disabled people before they get to work.
These are the elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree and out of 2.3 million university students there are only 10,000 disabled.
And finally - long-term unemployment is very prevalent: 53% for the disabled versus 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work and that constitute the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of the Tremplin Association, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There are still unspoken ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that the managers surveyed had a "weak level of knowledge about people with disabilities" with an "excessive idea of people on a wheelchair and mental or mental disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, indicate a state equal to 2.6%.
“We are now at around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, which is charged with collecting fees from companies that do not comply with the law.
The evidence is the number of "fined" enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
